huntBios.GENERAL_INFORMATION:
The majority of land is managed by BLM and US forest Service. There is a DWR Wildlife Management Area (WMA) known as the Pine Canyon WMA. This area is managed for wildlife and the DWR encourages hunting on all WMA’s. Pine Canyon generally holds a few deer during the hunting seasons. Heaston East CWMU and Camp Williams Military Base are not included in any on these hunts.

Most hunters plan on spending 3-4 days hunting. There are few water sources so plan on bringing extra water in with you. Some hunters who do not have much horse experience camp at the trail heads and hike in and out every day. I would plan on a very challenging and rewarding hunt. Be aware of private land. Review your maps frequently to avoid trespass issues especially in Ophir Canyon. This area is patrolled quite frequently by DWR personnel. Keep this in mind when you are transporting your game. Try to make it easy to access the permit and tag on the animal.
huntBios.SAFETY_CONS: There are very remote location with a few areas having limited access.  Cellular phone coverage is fair over most this hunt unit.  Digital cell phones may show several bars but cannot always connect due to the distance to the cell towers.  Satellite phones do work in the area.  The Biologist suggests handheld radios and even a "Spot Tracker" type of satellite messaging device for safety.  Make sure someone knows where you plan to camp and when you will return.
huntBios.WEATHER_CONS: The weather on this hunt unit can vary dramatically during the hunting season.  Be prepared for rain, lightening, snow, wind and heat.  Thunder storms can cause muddy road conditions and flash floods in this region.  Most hunters struggle with meat spoiling in the heat.  I would plan on hot weather and plan accordingly.
huntBios.MANAGEMENT_OBJ: 16.9~11600~9600~15–17~18.3~~~~~~~~For more detailed information on population and objective data please see the Big Game Annual Report Page.
huntBios.BIOLOGIST_NOTES:
A good spotting scope and binoculars are essential for scouting deer in this area.  Scouting is most effective mid-summer.  If you are able to place trail cameras on the remote springs and water holes you will be able to pattern the movements of the bucks.  In the hot early fall temperatures I would expect to see the most animals at prime time (1/2 hour before dawn and an hour before sunset).  There are several recovering burned areas that have produced large amounts of edge that is excellent for deer. Deer spend a lot of time in the aspen patches where there is a good understory of grass and forbs.       

There are very few signs on the trails.  I would bring a good map, compass, GPS, and if possible someone who is familiar with the area.  If you have never set foot in this unit, it might appear small on a map but on the ground it is quite a large area.

huntMaster.HARVEST_REPORTING: Voluntary: The DWR conducts random surveys for all general season hunts. You may be contacted via phone to participate in this survey.

huntBoundaryInfos.LAND_OWNERSHIP: The majority of land is managed by USFS, BLM and private ownership. The northeast portion of the Oquirrh Mountains is privately owned (Rio Tinto-Kennecott) and is a CWMU. Hunters should become familiar with the property boundary.
huntBoundaryInfos.WMA_IN_UNIT: Pine Canyon and Walt Fitzgerald WMAs
huntBoundaryInfos.CAMPGRND_INFO:
There are many dispersed camping sites within this unit, and developed campgrounds in North and South Willow Canyons, Grantsville Reservoir, Middle Canyon, Settlement Canyon and Ophir Canyon.
Bureau of Land Management: Please direct all questions regarding roads, maps and camping to the BLM Salt Lake Field Office https://www.blm.gov/office/salt-lake-field-office or (801) 320-8300

Forest Service: Please direct all questions regarding roads, maps and camping to the USFS Salt Lake Ranger district http://www.fs.fed.us or (801) 733-2660
There is no camping allowed on DWR WMA’s in this area.
huntBoundaryInfos.PRIM_ACCESS_PTS: Highways 73, 36, 199, Mormon Trail Road, Skull Valley Road, Butterfield Canyon Road, and West Canyon
huntBoundaryInfos.SUGGESTED_MAPS: BLM 1:100,000 Scale Maps: Rush Valley, Tooele
huntBoundaryInfos.ATV_VEH_ACCESS:
Generally, there is good ATV access on this unit. Please contact the USFS or BLM for the latest on ATV access.
Tooele County has information on county trails

http://www.tooelecountytrails.com/trails_map.html
huntBoundaryInfos.PRIV_TRIBE_LAND_ISSUES: All Tribal Lands are excluded from this hunt unit. The Skull Valley Goshute Tribe does not allow hunters across tribal lands to access Forest Service or BLM lands. Hunting on military lands (e.g. Tooele Army Depot North and South) is not permitted.
huntBoundaryInfos.BOUNDARY_DESCRIPTION: Salt Lake, Tooele and Utah counties--Boundary begins at I-15 and I-80 in Salt Lake City; south on I-15 to SR-73; west on SR-73 to Pony Express Road; west on this road to Faust Junction and SR-36; south on SR-36 to Pony Express Road; west on this road to the Skull Valley road; north on this road to I-80 at Rowley Junction; east on I-80 to I-15. The Pine Springs Conservation Wildlife Management Area is closed to motorized travel year-round. EXCLUDES ALL NATIVE AMERICAN TRUST LANDS WITHIN THIS BOUNDARY. Excludes all CWMUs. USGS 1:100,000 Maps: Provo, Rush Valley, Salt Lake City, Tooele. Boundary questions? Call the Springville office, (801) 491-5678.
